## Maintenance and Operations

### Rotating External ID

Rotate the External ID quarterly for security:

**1. Generate new External ID:**
```bash
NEW_EXTERNAL_ID=$(python3 -c "import uuid; print(f'pulldb-external-{uuid.uuid4()}')")
echo "New External ID: $NEW_EXTERNAL_ID"
```

**2. Update trust policy in production account:**
```bash
export AWS_PROFILE=prod-admin

# Create updated trust policy with new ExternalId
cat > updated-trust-policy.json <<EOF
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": {
        "AWS": "arn:aws:iam::222222222222:root"
      },
      "Action": "sts:AssumeRole",
      "Condition": {
        "StringEquals": {
          "sts:ExternalId": "$NEW_EXTERNAL_ID"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
EOF

aws iam update-assume-role-policy \
    --role-name pulldb-cross-account-read-role \
    --policy-document file://updated-trust-policy.json
```

**3. Update dev account profile configuration:**
```bash
# Edit ~/.aws/config
nano ~/.aws/config

# Update external_id line:
# external_id = pulldb-external-<new-uuid>
```

**4. Test access still works:**
```bash
AWS_PROFILE=pr-prod-cross-account aws sts get-caller-identity
```

### Rotating Dev User Access Keys

Rotate access keys every 90 days:

```bash
export AWS_PROFILE=dev-admin

# Create new key
NEW_KEY=$(aws iam create-access-key --user-name pulldb-dev-user)
echo "$NEW_KEY" | jq '.'

# Update local credentials
aws configure --profile pr-dev
# Enter new access key ID and secret

# Test new key works
AWS_PROFILE=pr-dev aws sts get-caller-identity

# Deactivate old key
aws iam update-access-key \
    --user-name pulldb-dev-user \
    --access-key-id OLD_KEY_ID \
    --status Inactive

# After 24 hours of verification, delete old key
aws iam delete-access-key \
    --user-name pulldb-dev-user \
    --access-key-id OLD_KEY_ID
```

### Monitoring Cross-Account Access

**Query CloudTrail for assume role events:**

```bash
export AWS_PROFILE=prod-admin

# List recent AssumeRole events
aws cloudtrail lookup-events \
    --lookup-attributes AttributeKey=EventName,AttributeValue=AssumeRole \
    --max-results 20 \
    --query 'Events[*].[EventTime,Username,EventName]' \
    --output table
```

**Create CloudWatch alarm for excessive access attempts:**

```bash
export AWS_PROFILE=prod-admin

aws cloudwatch put-metric-alarm \
    --alarm-name pulldb-excessive-assume-role \
    --metric-name AssumeRoleCount \
    --namespace AWS/IAM \
    --statistic Sum \
    --period 3600 \
    --threshold 100 \
    --comparison-operator GreaterThanThreshold \
    --alarm-actions arn:aws:sns:us-east-1:111111111111:security-alerts
```

---

## Production Deployment Considerations

For production pullDB deployment on EC2 in the dev account:

### Option 1: EC2 Instance Profile (Recommended)

Instead of using IAM user credentials, attach an instance profile:

**1. Create EC2 role in dev account:**
```bash
export AWS_PROFILE=dev-admin

# Create trust policy for EC2
cat > ec2-trust-policy.json <<EOF
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": {
        "Service": "ec2.amazonaws.com"
      },
      "Action": "sts:AssumeRole"
    }
  ]
}
EOF

# Create role
aws iam create-role \
    --role-name pulldb-ec2-role \
    --assume-role-policy-document file://ec2-trust-policy.json

# Attach the assume production role policy
aws iam attach-role-policy \
    --role-name pulldb-ec2-role \
    --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::222222222222:policy/pulldb-assume-prod-role-policy

# Create instance profile
aws iam create-instance-profile \
    --instance-profile-name pulldb-ec2-instance-profile

# Add role to instance profile
aws iam add-role-to-instance-profile \
    --instance-profile-name pulldb-ec2-instance-profile \
    --role-name pulldb-ec2-role
```

**2. Attach to EC2 instance:**
```bash
export AWS_PROFILE=dev-admin

aws ec2 associate-iam-instance-profile \
    --instance-id i-1234567890abcdef0 \
    --iam-instance-profile Name=pulldb-ec2-instance-profile
```

**3. No credentials in .env needed:**

On the EC2 instance, credentials are automatically provided via instance metadata. The same `pr-prod-cross-account` profile in `~/.aws/config` will work automatically.

### Option 2: AWS Secrets Manager for Access Keys

Store IAM user credentials in Secrets Manager instead of `.env`:

```bash
export AWS_PROFILE=dev-admin

aws secretsmanager create-secret \
    --name pulldb/dev/aws-credentials \
    --description "AWS credentials for pullDB cross-account access" \
    --secret-string '{
      "aws_access_key_id": "AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE",
      "aws_secret_access_key": "wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY"
    }'
```

Update pullDB to fetch credentials from Secrets Manager on startup.

